EDA¶

Language, License, Commits, and Files can be joined on repo name. Contents and Files can be joined on ID

First, We will remove NULLS as rows containing NULLS and NA have incomplete information and therefore are not as useful. So, to cut down on the volume of data we will be analyzing, we will remove them.

In [ ]:

df_contents_cleaned = df_contents_cleaned.dropDuplicates()

Timeline Analysis¶

As we are dealing with big data, we should first take a sample of the data to understand the timeline. In addition, this sample much be a continuous chunk of data. We will take a 5% sample as specified.

For timeline analysis, we will look at the commits df as it contains the date the author launched the project.

commits_filtered = commits_filtered.withColumn("commit_date", to_date(from_unixtime(col("author_time_sec"))))

commit_counts = commits_filtered.groupBy("commit_date").agg(count("*").alias("commit_count"))
commit_counts = commit_counts.orderBy("commit_date")

commit_counts_pd = commit_counts.toPandas()
commit_counts_pd["commit_date"] = pd.to_datetime(commit_counts_pd["commit_date"])
commit_counts_pd = commit_counts_pd[(commit_counts_pd["commit_date"].dt.year >= 2000) & (commit_counts_pd["commit_date"].dt.year <= 2020)]

plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))

plt.title("Commits per Day (2000 - 2020)")

When plotting every month of each year we see a lot of noise, therefore we will now aggregate months and plot each year in hopes of reducing noise in the large amounts of data

In [ ]:
commit_counts_pd['commit_date'] = pd.to_datetime(commit_counts_pd['commit_date'])

commit_counts_pd['year_month'] = commit_counts_pd['commit_date'].dt.to_period('M')
monthly_commit_counts = commit_counts_pd.groupby('year_month')['commit_count'].sum().reset_index()

monthly_commit_counts['year_month'] = monthly_commit_counts['year_month'].astype(str)

plt.figure(figsize=(12,6))
plt.plot(monthly_commit_counts['year_month'], monthly_commit_counts['commit_count'], marker='o', linestyle='-')

plt.xticks(monthly_commit_counts['year_month'][::12], rotation=45)
plt.xlabel("Year")
plt.ylabel("Number of Commits")
plt.title("Commits per Month (2000-2020)")
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()

Above we see the timeline spread from 2000 to 2020 for the number of commits. Now, we can start to visualize the regions where there are spikes and falls. In this case, we classify spikes where the next month is atleast 100% higher than the previous one, and a fall is when the month is atleast 50% less than the previous one.

In [ ]:
df = monthly_commit_counts.copy()

df = df.sort_values(by='year_month')

df['prev_commit_count'] = df['commit_count'].shift(1)
df['change_percent'] = (df['commit_count'] - df['prev_commit_count']) / df['prev_commit_count'] * 100
spikes = df[df['change_percent'] > 100]
falls = df[df['change_percent'] < -50]

plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
plt.plot(df['year_month'], df['commit_count'], marker='o', linestyle='-', label="Commits per Month"
plt.scatter(spikes['year_month'], spikes['commit_count'], color='red', label="Spikes", zorder=3)
plt.scatter(falls['year_month'], falls['commit_count'], color='blue', label="Falls", zorder=3)

plt.xlabel("Year-Month")
plt.ylabel("Number of Commits")
plt.title("Commits per Month (2000-2020) with Spikes and Falls")
plt.legend()
plt.xticks(rotation=45)
plt.grid(True, linestyle='--', alpha=0.5)
plt.show()


print("Detected Spikes:")
print(spikes[['year_month', 'commit_count']])

print(falls[['year_month', 'commit_count']])

def compute_duplication_for_language(df_lang, threshold=0.5, sample_fraction=0.001):
    
    df_cleaned = df_lang.select(
        lower(regexp_replace(col("subject"), r"[^a-zA-Z0-9\s]", "")).alias("subject_clean"),
        lower(regexp_replace(col("message"), r"[^a-zA-Z0-9\s]", "")).alias("message_clean")
    ).na.drop(subset=["subject_clean","message_clean"])
    
    df_text = df_cleaned.withColumn("text", concat_ws(" ", col("subject_clean"), col("message_clean")))
    
    tokenizer = Tokenizer(inputCol="text", outputCol="tokens")
    df_tokens = tokenizer.transform(df_text).filter(size(col("tokens")) > 0)

    df_sampled = df_tokens.sample(fraction=sample_fraction, seed=42)
    
    hashingTF = HashingTF(inputCol="tokens", outputCol="raw_features", numFeatures=512)
    df_tf = hashingTF.transform(df_sampled)
    
    idf = IDF(inputCol="raw_features", outputCol="features")
    idf_model = idf.fit(df_tf)
    df_tfidf = idf_model.transform(df_tf)
    
    brp = BucketedRandomProjectionLSH(
        inputCol="features",
        outputCol="hashes",
        bucketLength=1.0,  
        numHashTables=1   
    )
    brp_model = brp.fit(df_tfidf)
    df_lsh = brp_model.transform(df_tfidf)
    
    similar_pairs = brp_model.approxSimilarityJoin(
        df_lsh, df_lsh, threshold=threshold, distCol="euclid_dist"
    ).select(
        F.col("datasetA.text").alias("textA"),
        F.col("datasetB.text").alias("textB"),
        F.col("euclid_dist")
    ).filter("textA != textB")
    
    duplicate_count = similar_pairs.count()
    total_count = df_lsh.count()
    unique_count = total_count - duplicate_count
    
    return (duplicate_count, total_count, unique_count)

results = []
for lang in top_5_langs:
    print(f"\n=== Processing language: {lang} ===")
    df_lang = df_joined.filter(col("language_name") == lang)
    
    dup_count, total_count, unique_count = compute_duplication_for_language(
        df_lang, threshold=0.5, sample_fraction=0.01
    )
    
    dup_ratio = dup_count / total_count if total_count > 0 else 0.0
    
    results.append((lang, dup_count, total_count, unique_count, dup_ratio))
    print(f"Total lines: {total_count}, Duplicates: {dup_count}, Unique: {unique_count}, Dup Ratio: {dup_ratio:.2%}")
